# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dc-motors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In electrical engineering, the **armature** is the winding (or set of windings) of an electric machine which carries alternating current.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The armature windings conduct AC even on DC machines, due to the commutator action (which periodically reverses current direction) or due to electronic commutation, as in brushless DC motors.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The armature can be on either the rotor (rotating part) or the stator (field coil, stationary part), depending on the type of electric machine.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Shapes of armatures used in motors include double-T and triple-T armatures.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The armature windings interact with the magnetic field (magnetic flux) in the air-gap; the magnetic field is generated either by permanent magnets, or electromagnets formed by a conducting coil.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The armature must carry current, so it is always a conductor or a conductive coil, oriented normal to both the field and to the direction of motion, torque (rotating machine), or force (linear machine).
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The first is to carry current across the field, thus creating shaft torque in a rotating machine or force in a linear machine.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The second role is to generate an electromotive force (EMF).
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In the armature, an electromotive force is created by the relative motion of the armature and the field.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] When the machine or motor is used as a motor, this EMF opposes the armature current, and the armature converts electrical power to mechanical power in the form of torque, and transfers it via the shaft.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] When the machine is used as a generator, the armature EMF drives the armature current, and the shaft's movement is converted to electrical power.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In an induction generator, generated power is drawn from the stator.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] A growler is used to check the armature for short and open circuits and leakages to ground.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The word *armature* was first used in its electrical sense, i.e.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] *keeper of a magnet*, in mid 19th century.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The parts of an alternator or related equipment can be expressed in either mechanical terms or electrical terms.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Although distinctly separate these two sets of terminology are frequently used interchangeably or in combinations that include one mechanical term and one electrical term.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] This may cause confusion when working with compound machines like brushless alternators, or in conversation among people who are accustomed to work with differently configured machinery.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In most generators, the field magnet is rotating, and is part of the rotor, while the armature is stationary, and is part of the stator.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Both motors and generators can be built either with a stationary armature and a rotating field or a rotating armature and a stationary field.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The pole piece of a permanent magnet or electromagnet and the moving, iron part of a solenoid, especially if the latter acts as a switch or relay, may also be referred to as armatures.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In a DC machine, two sources of magnetic fluxes are present; 'armature flux' and 'main field flux'.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The effect of armature flux on the main field flux is called "armature reaction".
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The armature reaction changes the distribution of the magnetic field, which affects the operation of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The effects of the armature flux can be offset by adding a compensating winding to the main poles, or in some machines adding intermediate magnetic poles, connected in the armature circuit.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Armature reaction is essential in amplidyne rotating amplifiers.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Armature reaction drop is the effect of a magnetic field on the distribution of the flux under main poles of a generator.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Since an armature is wound with coils of wire, a magnetic field is set up in the armature whenever a current flows in the coils.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] This field is at right angles to the generator field and is called cross magnetization of the armature.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The effect of the armature field is to distort the generator field and shift the neutral plane.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The neutral plane is the position where the armature windings are moving parallel to the magnetic flux lines, that is why an axis lying in this plane is called as magnetic neutral axis (MNA).
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] This effect is known as armature reaction and is proportional to the current flowing in the armature coils.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The geometrical neutral axis (GNA) is the axis that bisects the angle between the centre line of adjacent poles.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The magnetic neutral axis (MNA) is the axis drawn perpendicular to the mean direction of the flux passing through the centre of the armature.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] No e.m.f. is produced in the armature conductors along this axis because then they cut no flux.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] When no current is there in the armature conductors, the MNA coincides with GNA.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The brushes of a generator must be set in the neutral plane; that is, they must contact segments of the commutator that are connected to armature coils having no induced emf.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] If the brushes were contacting commutator segments outside the neutral plane, they would short-circuit "live" coils and cause arcing and loss of power.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Without armature reaction, the magnetic neutral axis (MNA) would coincide with geometrical neutral axis (GNA).
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Armature reaction causes the neutral plane to shift in the direction of rotation, and if the brushes are in the neutral plane at no load, that is, when no armature current is flowing, they will not be in the neutral plane when armature current is flowing.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] For this reason it is desirable to incorporate a corrective system into the generator design.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] These are two principal methods by which the effect of armature reaction is overcome.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The first method is to shift the position of the brushes so that they are in the neutral plane when the generator is producing its normal load current. in the other method, special field poles, called interpoles, are installed in the generator to counteract the effect of armature reaction.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The brush-setting method is satisfactory in installations in which the generator operates under a fairly constant load.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] If the load varies to a marked degree, the neutral plane will shift proportionately, and the brushes will not be the correct position at all times.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The brush-setting method is the most common means of correcting for armature reaction in small generators (those producing approximately 1,000 W or less).
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Larger generators require the use of interpoles.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Coils of the winding are distributed over the entire surface of the air gap, which may be the rotor or the stator of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In a "lap" winding, there are as many current paths between the brush (or line) connections as there are poles in the field winding.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] In a "wave" winding, there are only two paths, and there are as many coils in series as half the number of poles.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] So, for a given rating of machine, a wave winding is more suitable for large currents and low voltages.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Windings are held in slots in the rotor or armature covered by stator magnets.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] The exact distribution of the windings and selection of the number of slots per pole of the field greatly influences the design of the machine and its performance, affecting such factors as commutation in a DC machine or the waveform of an AC machine.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Armature wiring is made from copper or aluminum.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Copper armature wiring enhances electrical efficiencies due to its higher electrical conductivity.
[src:dc-motors/armature-electrical] Aluminum armature wiring is lighter and less expensive than copper.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] In electromechanics, the **counter-electromotive force** (also called **counter EMF**, **CEMF** or **back EMF**), is the opposing electromotive force (EMF) caused by a changing current.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] The changing current leads to a changing magnetic field, and hence induces an EMF in the circuit by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] For example, the voltage appearing across an inductor or coil is due to a change in current which causes a change in the magnetic field within the coil, and therefore the self-induced voltage.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] The polarity of the voltage at every moment opposes that of the change in applied voltage, to keep the current constant.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] This effect is not due to the motor's inductance, which generates a voltage in opposition to a changing current via Faraday's law, but a separate phenomenon.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] That is, the back-EMF is also due to inductance and Faraday's law, but occurs even when the motor current is not changing, and arises from the geometric considerations of an armature spinning in a magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] This voltage is in series with and opposes the original applied voltage and is called "back-electromotive force" (by Lenz's law).
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] With a lower overall voltage across the motor's internal resistance as the motor turns faster, the current flowing into the motor decreases.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] One practical application of this phenomenon is to indirectly measure motor speed and position, as the back-EMF is proportional to the rotational speed of the armature.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] In motor control and robotics, back-EMF often refers most specifically to actually using the voltage generated by a spinning motor to infer the speed of the motor's rotation, for use in better controlling the motor in specific ways.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] To observe the effect of back-EMF of a motor, one can perform this simple exercise: with an incandescent light on, cause a large motor such as a drill press, saw, air conditioner compressor, or vacuum cleaner to start.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] The light may dim briefly as the motor starts.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] When the armature is not turning (called locked rotor) there is no back-EMF and the motor's current draw is quite high.
[src:dc-motors/back-electromotive-force] If the motor's starting current is high enough, it will pull the line voltage down enough to cause noticeable dimming of the light.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A **brushed DC electric motor** is an internally commutated electric motor designed to be run from a direct current power source and utilizing an electric brush for contact.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Existing DC generators use a commutator to achieve DC output instead of AC output, without commutation of voltage or current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] However, because the rotor rotates, the existing voltage-time curve resembles y = a |sin(t)|, causing the voltage to not always be at its maximum output voltage.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] If the rotor's motion were changed from rotation to repeatedly oscillating and cutting the magnetic field lines perpendicular to them, the voltage output efficiency could be increased, making it closer to a straight line, i.e., y = a.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The higher the oscillation frequency, the closer it should be to a straight line.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Brushed motors were the first commercially important application of electric power to driving mechanical energy, and DC distribution systems were used for more than 100 years to operate motors in commercial and industrial buildings.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors can be varied in speed by changing the operating voltage or the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Depending on the connections of the field to the power supply, the speed and torque characteristics of a brushed motor can be altered to provide steady speed or speed inversely proportional to the mechanical load.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Brushed motors continue to be used for electrical propulsion, cranes, paper machines and steel rolling mills.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Since the brushes wear down and require replacement, brushless DC motors using power electronic devices have displaced brushed motors from many applications.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The following graphics illustrate a simple, two-pole, brushed, DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] and drawn toward the right, causing rotation.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When the armature becomes horizontally aligned, the torque becomes zero.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] At this point, the commutator reverses the direction of current through the coil, reversing the magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When a current passes through the coil wound around a soft iron core situated inside an external magnetic field, the side of the positive pole is acted upon by an upwards force, while the other side is acted upon by a downward force.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] According to Fleming's left hand rule, the forces cause a turning effect on the coil, making it rotate.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] To make the motor rotate in a constant direction, *direct current* commutators make the current reverse in direction every half a cycle (in a two-pole motor) thus causing the motor to continue to rotate in the same direction.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A problem with the motor shown above is that when the plane of the coil is parallel to the magnetic field—i.e. when the rotor poles are 90 degrees from the stator poles—the torque is zero.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In the pictures above, this occurs when the core of the coil is horizontal—the position it is just about to reach in the next-to-last picture on the right.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The motor would not be able to start in this position.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] However, once it was started, it would continue to rotate through this position by momentum.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] There is a second problem with this simple pole design.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] At the zero-torque position, both commutator brushes are touching (bridging) both commutator plates, resulting in a short circuit.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The power leads are shorted together through the commutator plates, and the coil is also short-circuited through both brushes (the coil is shorted twice, once through each brush independently).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Note that this problem is independent of the non-starting problem above; even if there were a high current in the coil at this position, there would still be zero torque.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The problem here is that this short uselessly consumes power without producing any motion (nor even any coil current.) In a low-current battery-powered demonstration this short-circuiting is generally not considered harmful.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] However, if a two-pole motor were designed to do actual work with several hundred watts of power output, this shorting could result in severe commutator overheating, brush damage, and potential welding of the brushes—if they were metallic—to the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Carbon brushes, which are often used, would not weld.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In any case, a short like this is very wasteful, drains batteries rapidly and, at a minimum, requires power supply components to be designed to much higher standards than would be needed just to run the motor without the shorting.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] One simple solution is to put a gap between the commutator plates which is wider than the ends of the brushes.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This increases the zero-torque range of angular positions but eliminates the shorting problem; if the motor is started spinning by an outside force it will continue spinning.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] With this modification, it can also be effectively turned off simply by stalling (stopping) it in a position in the zero-torque (i.e. commutator non-contacting) angle range.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This design is sometimes seen in homebuilt hobby motors, e.g. for science fairs and such designs can be found in some published science project books.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A clear downside of this simple solution is that the motor now coasts through a substantial arc of rotation twice per revolution and the torque is pulsed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Another disadvantage is that, since the coils have a measure of self inductance, current flowing in them cannot suddenly stop.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The current attempts to jump the opening gap between the commutator segment and the brush, causing arcing.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Even for fans and flywheels, the clear weaknesses remaining in this design—especially that it is not self-starting from all positions—make it impractical for working use, especially considering the better alternatives that exist.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Unlike the demonstration motor above, DC motors are commonly designed with more than two poles, are able to start from any position, and do not have any position where current can flow without producing electromotive power by passing through some coil.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Many common small brushed DC motors used in toys and small consumer appliances, the simplest mass-produced DC motors to be found, have three-pole armatures.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The brushes can now bridge two adjacent commutator segments without causing a short circuit.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] These three-pole armatures also have the advantage that current from the brushes either flows through two coils in series or through just one coil.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Starting with the current in an individual coil at half its nominal value (as a result of flowing through two coils in series), it rises to its nominal value and then falls to half this value.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The sequence then continues with current in the reverse direction.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This results in a closer step-wise approximation to the ideal sinusoidal coil current, producing a more even torque than the two-pole motor where the current in each coil is closer to a square wave.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Since current changes are half those of a comparable two-pole motor, arcing at the brushes is consequently less.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] If the shaft of a DC motor is turned by an external force, the motor will act like a generator and produce an Electromotive force (EMF).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] During normal operation, the spinning of the motor produces a voltage, known as the counter-EMF (CEMF) or back EMF, because it opposes the applied voltage on the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The back EMF is the reason that the motor when free-running does not appear to have the same low electrical resistance as the wire contained in its winding.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This is the same EMF that is produced when the motor is used as a generator (for example when an electrical load, such as a light bulb, is placed across the terminals of the motor and the motor shaft is driven with an external torque).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Therefore, the total voltage drop across a motor consists of the CEMF voltage drop, and the parasitic voltage drop resulting from the internal resistance of the armature's windings.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As an unloaded DC motor spins, it generates a backwards-flowing electromotive force that resists the current being applied to the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The current through the motor drops as the rotational speed increases, and a free-spinning motor has very little current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] It is only when a load is applied to the motor that slows the rotor that the current draw through the motor increases.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a dynamo, a plane through the centers of the contact areas where a pair of brushes touch the commutator and parallel to the axis of rotation of the armature is referred to as the *commutating plane*.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In this diagram the commutating plane is shown for just one of the brushes, assuming the other brush made contact on the other side of the commutator with radial symmetry, 180 degrees from the brush shown.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a real dynamo, the field is never perfectly uniform.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Instead, as the rotor spins it induces field effects which drag and distort the magnetic lines of the outer non-rotating stator.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The faster the rotor spins, the further the degree of field distortion.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Because the dynamo operates most efficiently with the rotor field at right angles to the stator field, it is necessary to either retard or advance the brush position to put the rotor's field into the correct position to be at a right angle to the distorted field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] These field effects are reversed when the direction of spin is reversed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] It is therefore difficult to build an efficient reversible commutated dynamo, since for highest field strength it is necessary to move the brushes to the opposite side of the normal neutral plane.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The effect can be considered to be somewhat similar to timing advance in an internal combustion engine.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Generally a dynamo that has been designed to run at a certain fixed speed will have its brushes permanently fixed to align the field for highest efficiency at that speed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] DC machines with wound stators compensate the distortion with commutating field windings and compensation windings.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors are constructed with wound rotors and either wound or permanent-magnet stators.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The field coils have conventionally existed in four basic formats: *separately excited* (*sepex*), *series-wound*, *shunt-wound*, and a combination of the latter two, *compound-wound*.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a series-wound motor, the field coils are connected electrically in series with the armature coils (via the brushes).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a shunt-wound motor, the field coils are connected in parallel, or *shunted* to the armature coils.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a separately excited (sepex) motor, the field coils are supplied from an independent source, such as a motor–generator, and the field current is unaffected by changes in the armature current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The sepex system was sometimes used in DC traction motors to facilitate control of wheelslip.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Permanent-magnet types have some performance advantages over direct-current, excited, synchronous types, and have become predominant in fractional horsepower applications.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] They are smaller, lighter, more efficient and more reliable than other singly-fed electric machines.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Originally all large industrial DC motors used wound field or rotor magnets.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Permanent magnets have conventionally only been useful in small motors because it was difficult to find a material capable of retaining a high-strength field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Only recently have advances in materials technology allowed the creation of high-intensity permanent magnets, such as neodymium magnets, allowing the development of compact, high-power motors without the extra volume of field coils and excitation means.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] But as these high-performance permanent magnets are applied more in electric motor and generator systems other problems are realized (see Permanent magnet synchronous generator).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Traditionally, the field has been applied radially—in and away from the rotation axis of the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] However some designs have the field flowing along the axis of the motor, with the rotor cutting the field lines as it rotates.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This allows for much stronger magnetic fields, particularly if halbach arrays are employed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This, in turn, gives power to the motor at lower speeds.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] However, the focused flux density cannot rise about the limited residual flux density of the permanent magnet despite high coercivity and like all electric machines, the flux density of magnetic core saturation is the design constraint.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Generally, the rotational speed of a DC motor is proportional to the EMF in its coil (= the voltage applied to it minus voltage lost on its resistance), and the torque is proportional to the current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Speed control can be achieved by variable battery tappings, variable supply voltage, resistors or electronic controls.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A simulation example can be found here and.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The direction of a wound field DC motor can be changed by reversing either the field or armature connections but not both.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This is commonly done with a special set of contactors (direction contactors).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The effective voltage can be varied by inserting a series resistor or by an electronically controlled switching device made of thyristors, transistors, or, formerly, mercury arc rectifiers.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This provided three running speeds with minimal resistance losses.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] For starting and acceleration, additional control was provided by resistances.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This system has been superseded by electronic control systems.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The speed of a DC motor can be increased by field weakening.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Reducing the field strength is done by inserting resistance in series with a shunt field, or inserting resistances around a series-connected field winding, to reduce current in the field winding.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When the field is weakened, the back-emf reduces, so a larger current flows through the armature winding and this increases the speed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Field weakening is not used on its own but in combination with other methods, such as series–parallel control.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In a circuit known as a *chopper*, the average voltage applied to the motor is varied by switching the supply voltage very rapidly.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the *on* to *off* ratio is varied to alter the average applied voltage, the speed of the motor varies.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The percentage *on* time multiplied by the supply voltage gives the average voltage applied to the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Therefore, with a 100 V supply and a 25% *on* time, the average voltage at the motor will be 25 V.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] During the *off* time, the armature's inductance causes the current to continue through a diode called a *flyback diode*, in parallel with the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] At this point in the cycle, the supply current will be zero, and therefore the average motor current will always be higher than the supply current unless the percentage *on* time is 100%.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] At 100% *on* time, the supply and motor current are equal.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The rapid switching wastes less energy than series resistors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This method is also called pulse-width modulation (PWM) and is often controlled by a microprocessor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] An output filter is sometimes installed to smooth the average voltage applied to the motor and reduce motor noise.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Since the series-wound DC motor develops its highest torque at low speed, it is often used in traction applications such as electric locomotives, and trams.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Another application is starter motors for petrol and small diesel engines.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Series motors must never be used in applications where the drive can fail (such as belt drives).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the motor accelerates, the armature (and hence field) current reduces.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The reduction in field causes the motor to speed up, and in extreme cases the motor can even destroy itself, although this is much less of a problem in fan-cooled motors (with self-driven fans).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This can be a problem with railway motors in the event of a loss of adhesion since, unless quickly brought under control, the motors can reach speeds far higher than they would do under normal circumstances.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This can not only cause problems for the motors themselves and the gears, but due to the differential speed between the rails and the wheels it can also cause serious damage to the rails and wheel treads as they heat and cool rapidly.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Field weakening is used in some electronic controls to increase the top speed of an electric vehicle.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The simplest form uses a contactor and field-weakening resistor; the electronic control monitors the motor current and switches the field weakening resistor into circuit when the motor current reduces below a preset value (this will be when the motor is at its full design speed).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Once the resistor is in circuit, the motor will increase speed above its normal speed at its rated voltage.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When motor current increases, the control will disconnect the resistor and low speed torque is made available.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A Ward Leonard control is usually used for controlling a shunt or compound wound DC motor, and developed as a method of providing a speed-controlled motor from an AC supply, though it is not without its advantages in DC schemes.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The AC supply is used to drive an AC motor, usually an induction motor that drives a DC generator or dynamo.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The DC output from the armature is directly connected to the armature of the DC motor (sometimes but not always of identical construction).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The shunt field windings of both DC machines are independently excited through variable resistors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Extremely good speed control from standstill to full speed, and consistent torque, can be obtained by varying the generator and/or motor field current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This method of control was the *de facto* method from its development until it was superseded by solid state thyristor systems.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] It found service in almost any environment where good speed control was required, from passenger lifts through to large mine pit head winding gear and even industrial process machinery and electric cranes.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Its principal disadvantage was that three machines were required to implement a scheme (five in very large installations, as the DC machines were often duplicated and controlled by a tandem variable resistor).
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In many applications, the motor-generator set was often left permanently running, to avoid the delays that would otherwise be caused by starting it up as required.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Although electronic (thyristor) controllers have replaced most small to medium Ward-Leonard systems, some very large ones (thousands of horsepower) remain in service.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The field currents are much lower than the armature currents, allowing a moderate sized thyristor unit to control a much larger motor than it could control directly.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] For example, in one installation, a 300 amp thyristor unit controls the field of the generator.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The generator output current is in excess of 15,000 amperes, which would be prohibitively expensive (and inefficient) to control directly with thyristors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A DC motor's speed and torque characteristics vary according to three different magnetization sources, separately excited field, self-excited field or permanent-field, which are used selectively to control the motor over the mechanical load's range.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Self-excited field motors can be series, shunt, or a compound wound connected to the armature.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] With the shunt wound motor's high-resistance field winding connected in parallel with the armature, Vm, Rm and Ø are constant such that the no load to full load speed regulation is seldom more than 5%.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The series motor responds to increased load by slowing down; the current increases and the torque rises in proportional to the square of the current since the same current flows in both the armature and the field windings.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] If the motor is stalled, the current is limited only by the total resistance of the windings and the torque can be very high, but there is a danger of the windings becoming overheated.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Series wound motors were widely used as traction motors in rail transport of every kind, but are being phased out in favour of power inverter-fed AC induction motors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The counter EMF aids the armature resistance to limit the current through the armature.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When power is first applied to a motor, the armature does not rotate, the counter EMF is zero and the only factor limiting the armature current is the armature resistance.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the prospective current through the armature is very large, the need arises for an additional resistance in series with the armature to limit the current until the motor rotation can build up the counter EMF.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the motor rotation builds up, the resistance is gradually cut out.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The series wound DC motor's most notable characteristic is that its speed is almost entirely dependent on the torque required to drive the load.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This suits large inertial loads as motor accelerates from maximum torque, torque reducing gradually as speed increases.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the series motor's speed can be dangerously high, series motors are often geared or direct-connected to the load.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A permanent magnet DC motor is characterized by a linear relationship between stall torque when the torque is maximum with the shaft at standstill and no-load speed with no applied shaft torque and maximum output speed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] There is a quadratic power relationship between these two speed-axis points.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] To extend a DC motor's service life, protective devices and motor controllers are used to protect it from mechanical damage, excessive moisture, high dielectric stress and high temperature or thermal overloading.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] These protective devices sense motor fault conditions and either activate an alarm to notify the operator or automatically de-energize the motor when a faulty condition occurs.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] For overloaded conditions, motors are protected with thermal overload relays.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Bi-metal thermal overload protectors are embedded in the motor's windings and made from two dissimilar metals.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] They are designed such that the bimetallic strips will bend in opposite directions when a temperature set point is reached to open the control circuit and de-energize the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Heaters are external thermal overload protectors connected in series with the motor's windings and mounted in the motor contactor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Solder pot heaters melt in an overload condition, which cause the motor control circuit to de-energize the motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Bimetallic heaters function the same way as embedded bimetallic protectors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Fuses and circuit breakers are overcurrent or short circuit protectors.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Ground fault relays also provide overcurrent protection.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] They monitor the electric current between the motor's windings and earth system ground.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In motor-generators, reverse current relays prevent the battery from discharging and motorizing the generator.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Since D.C. motor field loss can cause a hazardous runaway or overspeed condition, loss of field relays are connected in parallel with the motor's field to sense field current.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When the field current decreases below a set point, the relay will deenergize the motor's armature.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] A locked rotor condition prevents a motor from accelerating after its starting sequence has been initiated.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Distance relays protect motors from locked-rotor faults.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Undervoltage motor protection is typically incorporated into motor controllers or starters.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In addition, motors can be protected from overvoltages or surges with isolation transformers, power conditioning equipment, MOVs, arresters and harmonic filters.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Environmental conditions, such as dust, explosive vapors, water, and high ambient temperatures, can adversely affect the operation of a DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] To protect a motor from these environmental conditions, the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) have standardized motor enclosure designs based upon the environmental protection they provide from contaminants.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Modern software can also be used in the design stage, such as Motor-CAD, to help increase the thermal efficiency of a motor.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The counter-emf aids the armature resistance to limit the current through the armature.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When power is first applied to a motor, the armature does not rotate.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] At that instant the counter-emf is zero and the only factor limiting the armature current is the armature resistance and inductance.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Usually the armature resistance of a motor is less than 1 Ω; therefore the current through the armature would be very large when the power is applied.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This current can make an excessive voltage drop affecting other equipment in the circuit and even trip overload protective devices.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Therefore, the need arises for an additional resistance in series with the armature to limit the current until the motor rotation can build up the counter-emf.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] When electrical and DC motor technology was first developed, much of the equipment was constantly tended by an operator trained in the management of motor systems.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The very first motor management systems were almost completely manual, with an attendant starting and stopping the motors, cleaning the equipment, repairing any mechanical failures, and so forth.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The first DC motor-starters were also completely manual, as shown in this image.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] Normally it took the operator about ten seconds to slowly advance the rheostat across the contacts to gradually increase input power up to operating speed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] There were two different classes of these rheostats, one used for starting only, and one for starting and speed regulation.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The starting rheostat was less expensive, but had smaller resistance elements that would burn out if required to run a motor at a constant reduced speed.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] This starter includes a no-voltage magnetic holding feature, which causes the rheostat to spring to the off position if power is lost, so that the motor does not later attempt to restart in the full-voltage position.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] It also has overcurrent protection that trips the lever to the off position if excessive current over a set amount is detected.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The incoming power wires are called L1 and L2.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] As the name implies there are only three connections to the starter, one to incoming power, one to the armature, and one to the field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The connections to the armature are called A1 and A2.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The ends of the field (excitement) coil are called F1 and F2.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In order to control the speed, a field rheostat is connected in series with the shunt field.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] One side of the line is connected to the arm of the starter.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The arm is spring-loaded so, it will return to the "Off" position when not held at any other position.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The four-point starter eliminates the drawback of the three-point starter.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] In addition to the same three points that were in use with the three-point starter, the other side of the line, L1, is the fourth point brought to the starter when the arm is moved from the "Off" position.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The coil of the holding magnet is connected across the line.
[src:dc-motors/brushed-dc-electric-motor] The holding magnet and starting resistors function identical as in the three-point starter.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] A **commutator** is a rotary electrical switch in certain types of electric motors and electrical generators that periodically reverses the current direction between the rotor and the external circuit.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] It consists of a cylinder composed of multiple metal contact segments on the rotating armature of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Two or more electrical contacts called "brushes" made of a soft conductive material like carbon press against the commutator, making sliding contact with successive segments of the commutator as it rotates.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The windings (coils of wire) on the armature are connected to the commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Commutators are used in direct current (DC) machines: dynamos (DC generators) and many DC motors as well as universal motors.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In a motor the commutator applies electric current to the windings.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] By reversing the current direction in the rotating windings each half turn, a steady rotating force (torque) is produced.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In a generator the commutator picks off the current generated in the windings, reversing the direction of the current with each half turn, serving as a mechanical rectifier to convert the alternating current from the windings to unidirectional direct current in the external load circuit.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The first direct current commutator-type machine, the dynamo, was built by Hippolyte Pixii in 1832, based on a suggestion by André-Marie Ampère.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Commutators are relatively inefficient, and also require periodic maintenance such as brush replacement.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Therefore, commutated machines are declining in use, being replaced by alternating current (AC) machines, and in recent years by brushless DC motors which use semiconductor switches.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] A commutator consists of a set of contact bars fixed to the rotating shaft of a machine, and connected to the armature windings.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] As the shaft rotates, the commutator reverses the flow of current in a winding.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] For a single armature winding, when the shaft has made one-half complete turn, the winding is now connected so that current flows through it in the opposite of the initial direction.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In a motor, the armature current causes the fixed magnetic field to exert a rotational force, or a torque, on the winding to make it turn.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In a generator, the mechanical torque applied to the shaft maintains the motion of the armature winding through the stationary magnetic field, inducing a current in the winding.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In both the motor and generator case, the commutator periodically reverses the direction of current flow through the winding so that current flow in the circuit external to the machine continues in only one direction.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Practical commutators have at least three contact segments, to prevent a "dead" spot where two brushes simultaneously bridge only two commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Brushes are made wider than the insulated gap, to ensure that brushes are always in contact with an armature coil.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] For commutators with at least three segments, although the rotor can potentially stop in a position where two commutator segments touch one brush, this only de-energizes one of the rotor arms while the others will still function correctly.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] With the remaining rotor arms, a motor can produce sufficient torque to begin spinning the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] A commutator consists of a set of copper segments, fixed around the part of the circumference of the rotating machine, or the rotor, and a set of spring-loaded brushes fixed to the stationary frame of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Two or more fixed brushes connect to the external circuit, either a source of current for a motor or a load for a generator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Commutator segments are connected to the coils of the armature, with the number of coils (and commutator segments) depending on the speed and voltage of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Large motors may have hundreds of segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Each conducting segment of the commutator is insulated from adjacent segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Mica was used on early machines and is still used on large machines.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Many other insulating materials are used to insulate smaller machines; plastics allow quick manufacture of an insulator, for example.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The segments are held onto the shaft using a dovetail shape on the edges or underside of each segment.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Insulating wedges around the perimeter of each segment are pressed so that the commutator maintains its mechanical stability throughout its normal operating range.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In small appliance and tool motors the segments are typically crimped permanently in place and cannot be removed.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] When the motor fails it is discarded and replaced.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] On large industrial machines (say, from several kilowatts to thousands of kilowatts in rating) it is economical to replace individual damaged segments, and so the end-wedge can be unscrewed and individual segments removed and replaced.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Replacing the copper and mica segments is commonly referred to as "refilling".
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Disposable, molded type commutators commonly found in smaller DC motors are becoming increasingly more common in larger electric motors.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Molded type commutators are not repairable and must be replaced if damaged.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Such requirements are common with traction, military, aerospace, nuclear, mining, and high speed applications where clamping failure and segment or insulation protrusion can lead to serious negative consequences.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Friction between the segments and the brushes eventually causes wear to both surfaces.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Carbon brushes, being made of a softer material, wear faster and may be designed to be replaced easily without dismantling the machine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Older copper brushes caused more wear to the commutator, causing deep grooving and notching of the surface over time.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The commutator on small motors (say, less than a kilowatt rating) is not designed to be repaired through the life of the device.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] On large industrial equipment, the commutator may be re-surfaced with abrasives, or the rotor may be removed from the frame, mounted in a large metal lathe, and the commutator resurfaced by cutting it down to a smaller diameter.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The largest of equipment can include a lathe turning attachment directly over the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Early machines used brushes made from strands of copper wire to contact the surface of the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] However, these hard metal brushes tended to scratch and groove the smooth commutator segments, eventually requiring resurfacing of the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] As the copper brushes wore away, the dust and pieces of the brush could wedge between commutator segments, shorting them and reducing the efficiency of the device.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Fine copper wire mesh or gauze provided better surface contact with less segment wear, but gauze brushes were more expensive than strip or wire copper brushes.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Modern rotating machines with commutators almost exclusively use carbon brushes, which may have copper powder mixed in to improve conductivity.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Metallic copper brushes can be found in toy or very small motors, such as the one illustrated above, and some motors which only operate very intermittently, such as automotive starter motors.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Motors and generators suffer from a phenomenon known as 'armature reaction', one of the effects of which is to change the position at which the current reversal through the windings should ideally take place as the loading varies.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Early machines had the brushes mounted on a ring that was provided with a handle.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] During operation, it was necessary to adjust the position of the brush ring to adjust the commutation to minimise the sparking at the brushes.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This process was known as 'rocking the brushes'.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Various developments took place to automate the process of adjusting the commutation and minimizing the sparking at the brushes.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] One of these was the development of 'high resistance brushes', or brushes made from a mixture of copper powder and carbon.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Although described as high resistance brushes, the resistance of such a brush was of the order of milliohms, the exact value dependent on the size and function of the machine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Also, the high resistance brush was not constructed like a brush but in the form of a carbon block with a curved face to match the shape of the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The high resistance or carbon brush is made large enough that it is significantly wider than the insulating segment that it spans (and on large machines may often span two insulating segments).
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The result of this is that as the commutator segment passes from under the brush, the current passing to it ramps down more smoothly than had been the case with pure copper brushes where the contact broke suddenly.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Similarly the segment coming into contact with the brush has a similar ramping up of the current.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Thus, although the current passing through the brush was more or less constant, the instantaneous current passing to the two commutator segments was proportional to the relative area in contact with the brush.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The introduction of the carbon brush had convenient side effects.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Carbon brushes tend to wear more evenly than copper brushes, and the soft carbon causes far less damage to the commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] There is less sparking with carbon as compared to copper, and as the carbon wears away, the higher resistance of carbon results in fewer problems from the dust collecting on the commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The ratio of copper to carbon can be changed for a particular purpose.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Brushes with higher copper content perform better with very low voltages and high current, while brushes with a higher carbon content are better for high voltage and low current.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] High copper content brushes typically carry 150 to 200 amperes per square inch of contact surface, while higher carbon content only carries 40 to 70 amperes per square inch.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The higher resistance of carbon also results in a greater voltage drop of 0.8 to 1.0 volts per contact, or 1.6 to 2.0 volts across the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] A spring is typically used with the brush, to maintain constant contact with the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] As the brush and commutator wear down, the spring steadily pushes the brush downwards towards the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Eventually the brush wears small and thin enough that steady contact is no longer possible or it is no longer securely held in the brush holder, and so the brush must be replaced.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] It is common for a flexible power cable to be directly attached to the brush, because current flowing through the support spring would cause heating, which may lead to a loss of metal temper and a loss of the spring tension.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] When a commutated motor or generator uses more power than a single brush is capable of conducting, an assembly of several brush holders is mounted in parallel across the surface of the very large commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This parallel holder distributes current evenly across all the brushes, and permits a careful operator to remove a bad brush and replace it with a new one, even as the machine continues to spin fully powered and under load.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] High power, high current commutated equipment is now uncommon, due to the less complex design of alternating current generators that permits a low current, high voltage spinning field coil to energize high current fixed-position stator coils.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This permits the use of very small singular brushes in the alternator design.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In this instance, the rotating contacts are continuous rings, called slip rings, and no switching happens.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Modern devices using carbon brushes usually have a maintenance-free design that requires no adjustment throughout the life of the device, using a fixed-position brush holder slot and a combined brush-spring-cable assembly that fits into the slot.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The worn brush is pulled out and a new brush inserted.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The different brush types make contact with the commutator in different ways.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Because copper brushes have the same hardness as the commutator segments, the rotor cannot be spun backwards against the ends of copper brushes without the copper digging into the segments and causing severe damage.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Consequently, strip/laminate copper brushes only make tangential contact with the commutator, while copper mesh and wire brushes use an inclined contact angle touching their edge across the segments of a commutator that can spin in only one direction.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The softness of carbon brushes permits direct radial end-contact with the commutator without damage to the segments, permitting easy reversal of rotor direction, without the need to reorient the brush holders for operation in the opposite direction.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Although never reversed, common appliance motors that use wound rotors, commutators and brushes have radial-contact brushes.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In the case of a reaction-type carbon brush holder, carbon brushes may be reversely inclined with the commutator so that the commutator tends to push against the carbon for firm contact.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The contact point where a brush touches the commutator is referred to as the *commutating plane*.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] To conduct sufficient current to or from the commutator, the brush contact area is not a thin line but instead a rectangular patch across the segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Typically the brush is wide enough to span 2.5 commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This means that two adjacent segments are electrically connected by the brush when it contacts both.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Most introductions to motor and generator design start with a simple two-pole device with the brushes arranged at a perfect 90-degree angle from the field.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This ideal is useful as a starting point for understanding how the fields interact but it is not how a motor or generator functions in actual practice.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In a real motor or generator, the field around the rotor is never perfectly uniform.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Instead, the rotation of the rotor induces field effects which drag and distort the magnetic lines of the outer non-rotating stator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The faster the rotor spins, the further this degree of field distortion.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Because a motor or generator operates most efficiently with the rotor field at right angles to the stator field, it is necessary to either retard or advance the brush position to put the rotor's field into the correct position to be at a right angle to the distorted field.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] These effects can be mitigated by a compensation winding in the face of the field pole that carries armature current.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The effect can be considered to be analogous to timing advance in an internal combustion engine.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Self-induction – The magnetic fields in each coil of wire join and compound together to create a magnetic field that resists changes in the current, which can be likened to the current having inertia.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In the coils of the rotor, even after the brush has been reached, currents tend to continue to flow for a brief moment, resulting in a wasted energy as heat due to the brush spanning across several commutator segments and the current short-circuiting across the segments.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] To minimize sparking at the brushes due to this short-circuiting, the brushes are advanced a few degrees further yet, beyond the advance for field distortions.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This moves the rotor winding undergoing commutation slightly forward into the stator field which has magnetic lines in the opposite direction and which oppose the field in the stator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This opposing field helps to reverse the lagging self-inducting current in the stator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] So even for a rotor which is at rest and initially requires no compensation for spinning field distortions, the brushes should still be advanced beyond the perfect 90-degree angle as taught in so many beginners textbooks, to compensate for self-induction.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Modern motor and generator devices with commutators are able to counteract armature reaction through the use of *interpoles*, which are small field coils and pole pieces positioned approximately halfway between the primary poles of the stator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] By applying a dynamic varying field to the interpoles as the load, RPM, or direction of rotation of the device changes, it is possible to balance out field distortions from armature reaction so that the brush position can remain fixed and sparking across the segments is minimized.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Although direct current motors and dynamos once dominated industry, the disadvantages of the commutator have caused a decline in the use of commutated machines in the last century.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] With the wide availability of alternating current, DC motors have been replaced by more efficient AC synchronous or induction motors.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In recent years, with the widespread availability of power semiconductors, in many remaining applications commutated DC motors have been replaced with "brushless direct current motors".
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] These don't have a commutator; instead the direction of the current is switched electronically.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] A sensor keeps track of the rotor position and semiconductor switches such as transistors reverse the current.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Operating life of these machines is much longer, limited mainly by bearing wear.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] These are single-phase AC-only motors with higher starting torque than could be obtained with split-phase starting windings, before high-capacitance (non-polar, relatively high-current electrolytic) starting capacitors became practical.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] They have a conventional wound stator as with any induction motor, but the wire-wound rotor is much like that with a conventional commutator.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Brushes opposite each other are connected to each other (not to an external circuit), and transformer action induces currents into the rotor that develop torque by repulsion.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] One variety, notable for having an adjustable speed, runs continuously with brushes in contact, while another uses repulsion only for high starting torque and in some cases lifts the brushes once the motor is running fast enough.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] In the latter case, all commutator segments are connected together as well, before the motor attains running speed.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Once at speed, the rotor windings become functionally equivalent to the squirrel-cage structure of a conventional induction motor, and the motor runs as such.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Commutators were used as simple forward-off-reverse switches for electrical experiments in physics laboratories.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This is similar in design to the commutators used in motors and dynamos.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] It was usually constructed of brass and ivory (later ebonite).
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] This consists of a block of wood or ebonite with four wells, containing mercury, which are cross connected by copper wires.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] The output is taken from a pair of curved copper wires which are moved to dip into one or other pair of mercury wells.
[src:dc-motors/commutator-electric] Instead of mercury, ionic liquids or other liquid metals such as galinstan can be used.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A **DC motor** is an electrical motor that uses direct current (DC) to produce mechanical force.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The most common types rely on magnetic forces produced by currents in the coils.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Nearly all types of DC motors have some internal mechanism, either electromechanical or electronic, to periodically change the direction of current in part of the motor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] DC motors were the first form of motors to be widely used, as they could be powered from existing direct-current lighting power distribution systems.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A DC motor's speed can be controlled over a wide range, using either a variable supply voltage or by changing the strength of current in its field windings.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Small DC motors are used in tools, toys, and appliances.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The universal motor, a lightweight brushed motor used for portable power tools and appliances can operate on direct current and alternating current.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Larger DC motors are currently used in propulsion of electric vehicles, elevator and hoists, and in drives for steel rolling mills.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The advent of power electronics has made replacement of DC motors with AC motors possible in many applications.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A coil of wire with a current running through it generates an electromagnetic field aligned with the center of the coil.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The direction and magnitude of the magnetic field produced by the coil can be changed with the direction and magnitude of the current flowing through it.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A simple DC motor has a stationary set of magnets in the stator and an armature with one or more windings of insulated wire wrapped around a soft iron core that concentrates the magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The windings usually have multiple turns around the core, and in large motors there can be several parallel current paths.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The ends of the wire winding are connected to a commutator.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The commutator allows each armature coil to be energized in turn and connects the rotating coils with the external power supply through brushes.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The total amount of current sent to the coil, the coil's size, and what it is wrapped around decide the strength of the electromagnetic field created.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The sequence of turning a particular coil on or off dictates what direction the effective electromagnetic fields are pointed.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] By turning on and off coils in sequence, a rotating magnetic field can be created.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] These rotating magnetic fields interact with the magnetic fields of the magnets (permanent or electromagnets) in the stationary part of the motor (stator) to create a torque on the armature which causes it to rotate.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] In some DC motor designs, the stator fields use electromagnets to create their magnetic fields which allows greater control over the motor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] At high power levels, DC motors are almost always cooled using forced air.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Different number of stator and armature fields as well as how they are connected provide different inherent speed and torque regulation characteristics.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The speed of a DC motor can be controlled by changing the voltage applied to the armature.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Variable resistance in the armature circuit or field circuit allows speed control.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Modern DC motors are often controlled by power electronics systems which adjust the voltage by "chopping" the DC current into on and off cycles which have an effective lower voltage.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The introduction of DC motors and an electrical grid system to run machinery starting in the 1870s started a new second Industrial Revolution.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] DC motors can operate directly from rechargeable batteries, providing the motive power for the first electric vehicles and today's hybrid cars and electric cars as well as driving a host of cordless tools.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Today DC motors are still found in applications as small as toys and disk drives, or in large sizes to operate steel rolling mills and paper machines.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Large DC motors with separately excited fields were generally used with winder drives for mine hoists, for high torque as well as smooth speed control using thyristor drives.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] These are now replaced with large AC motors with variable frequency drives.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] If external mechanical power is applied to a DC motor it acts as a DC generator, a dynamo.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This feature is used to slow down and recharge batteries on hybrid and electric cars or to return electricity back to the electric grid used on a street car or electric powered train line when they slow down.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This process is called regenerative braking on hybrid and electric cars.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] In diesel electric locomotives they also use their DC motors as generators to slow down but dissipate the energy in resistor stacks.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Newer designs are adding large battery packs to recapture some of this energy.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The brushed DC electric motor generates torque directly from DC power supplied to the motor by using internal commutation, stationary magnets (permanent or electromagnets), and rotating electromagnets.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Advantages of a brushed DC motor include low initial cost, high reliability, and simple control of motor speed.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Disadvantages are high maintenance and low life-span for high intensity uses.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Maintenance involves regularly replacing the carbon brushes and springs which carry the electric current, as well as cleaning or replacing the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] These components are necessary for transferring electrical power from outside the motor to the spinning wire windings of the rotor inside the motor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Brushes are usually made of graphite or carbon, sometimes with added dispersed copper to improve conductivity.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] In use, the soft brush material wears to fit the diameter of the commutator, and continues to wear.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A brush holder has a spring to maintain pressure on the brush as it shortens.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] For brushes intended to carry more than an ampere or two, a flying lead will be molded into the brush and connected to the motor terminals.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Very small brushes may rely on sliding contact with a metal brush holder to carry current into the brush, or may rely on a contact spring pressing on the end of the brush.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The brushes in very small, short-lived motors, such as are used in toys, may be made of a folded strip of metal that contacts the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Typical brushless DC motors use one or more permanent magnets in the rotor and electromagnets on the motor housing for the stator.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This design is mechanically simpler than that of brushed motors because it eliminates the complication of transferring power from outside the motor to the spinning rotor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The motor controller can sense the rotor's position via Hall effect sensors or similar devices and can precisely control the timing, phase, etc., of the current in the rotor coils to optimize torque, conserve power, regulate speed, and even apply some braking.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Advantages of brushless motors include long life span, little or no maintenance, and high efficiency.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Disadvantages include high initial cost, and more complicated motor speed controllers.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Some such brushless motors are sometimes referred to as "synchronous motors" although they have no external power supply to be synchronized with, as would be the case with normal AC synchronous motors.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Other types of DC motors require no commutation.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A permanent magnet (PM) motor does not have a field winding on the stator frame, instead relying on PMs to provide the magnetic field against which the rotor field interacts to produce torque.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Compensation windings in series with the armature may be used on large motors to improve commutation under load.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Because this field is fixed, it cannot be adjusted for speed control.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] PM fields (stators) are convenient in miniature motors to eliminate the power consumption of the field winding.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Most larger DC motors are of the "dynamo" type, which have stator windings.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Historically, PMs could not be made to retain high flux if they were disassembled; field windings were more practical to obtain the needed amount of flux.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] However, large PMs are costly, as well as dangerous and difficult to assemble; this favors wound fields for large machines.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] To minimize overall weight and size, miniature PM motors may use high energy magnets made with neodymium or other strategic elements; most such are neodymium-iron-boron alloy.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] With their higher flux density, electric machines with high-energy PMs are at least competitive with all optimally designed singly fed synchronous and induction electric machines.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Miniature motors resemble the structure in the illustration, except that they have at least three rotor poles (to ensure starting, regardless of rotor position) and their outer housing is a steel tube that magnetically links the exteriors of the curved field magnets.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A series DC motor connects the armature and field windings in series with a common D.C. power source.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The motor speed varies as a non-linear function of load torque and armature current; current is common to both the stator and rotor yielding current squared (I^2) behavior.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A series motor has very high starting torque and is commonly used for starting high inertia loads, such as trains, elevators or hoists.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This speed/torque characteristic is useful in applications such as dragline excavators, where the digging tool moves rapidly when unloaded but slowly when carrying a heavy load.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A series motor should never be started at no load.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] With no mechanical load on the series motor, the current is low, the counter-Electro motive force produced by the field winding is weak, and so the armature must turn faster to produce sufficient counter-EMF to balance the supply voltage.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Series motors called universal motors can be used on alternating current.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Since the armature voltage and the field direction reverse at the same time, torque continues to be produced in the same direction.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] However they run at a lower speed with lower torque on AC supply when compared to DC due to reactance voltage drop in AC which is not present in DC.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Since the speed is not related to the line frequency, universal motors can develop higher-than-synchronous speeds, making them lighter than induction motors of the same rated mechanical output.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This is a valuable characteristic for hand-held power tools.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Universal motors for commercial utility are usually of small capacity, not more than about 1 kW output.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] However, much larger universal motors were used for electric locomotives, fed by special low-frequency traction power networks to avoid problems with commutation under heavy and varying loads.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A shunt DC motor connects the armature and field windings in parallel or shunt with a common D.C. power source.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This type of motor has good speed regulation even as the load varies, but does not have the starting torque of a series DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] It is typically used for industrial, adjustable speed applications, such as machine tools, winding/unwinding machines and tensioners.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] A compound DC motor connects the armature and fields windings in a shunt and a series combination to give it characteristics of both a shunt and a series DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] This motor is used when both a high starting torque and good speed regulation is needed.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] The motor can be connected in two arrangements: cumulatively or differentially.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Cumulative compound motors connect the series field to aid the shunt field, which provides higher starting torque but less speed regulation.
[src:dc-motors/dc-motor] Differential compound DC motors have good speed regulation and are typically operated at constant speed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An **electric motor** is a machine that converts electrical energy into mechanical energy.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Most electric motors operate through the interaction between the motor's magnetic field and electric current in a wire winding to generate Lorentz force in the form of torque applied on the motor's shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An electric generator is mechanically identical to an electric motor but operates inversely, converting mechanical energy into electrical energy.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors can be powered by direct current (DC) sources, such as from batteries or rectifiers, or by alternating current (AC) sources, such as a power grid, inverters or electrical generators.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors may also be classified by considerations such as power source type, construction, application and type of motion output.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They can be brushed or brushless, single-phase, two-phase, or three-phase, axial or radial flux, and may be air-cooled or liquid-cooled.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Standardized electric motors provide power for industrial use.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The largest are used for marine propulsion, pipeline compression and pumped-storage applications, with output exceeding 100 megawatts.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Other applications include industrial fans, blowers and pumps, machine tools, household appliances, power tools, vehicles, and disk drives.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Small motors may be found in electric watches.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In certain applications, such as in regenerative braking with traction motors, electric motors can be used in reverse as generators to recover energy that might otherwise be lost as heat and friction.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors produce linear or rotary force (torque) intended to propel some external mechanism.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They are generally designed for continuous rotation, or for linear movement over a significant distance compared to its size.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Solenoids also convert electrical power to mechanical motion, but over only a limited distance.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An electric motor has two mechanical parts: the rotor, which moves, and the stator, which does not.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electrically, the motor consists of two parts, the field magnets and the armature, one of which is attached to the rotor and the other to the stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The magnets create a magnetic field that passes through the armature.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] These can be electromagnets or permanent magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The field magnet is usually on the stator and the armature on the rotor, but these may be reversed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor is the moving part that delivers the mechanical power.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor typically holds conductors that carry currents, on which the magnetic field of the stator exerts force to turn the shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The stator surrounds the rotor, and usually holds field magnets, which are either electromagnets (wire windings around a ferromagnetic iron core) or permanent magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] These create a magnetic field that passes through the rotor armature, exerting force on the rotor windings.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The stator core is made up of many thin metal sheets that are insulated from each other, called laminations.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] These laminations are made of electrical steel, which has a specified magnetic permeability, hysteresis, and saturation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Laminations reduce losses that would result from induced circulating eddy currents that would flow if a solid core were used.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Mains-powered AC motors typically immobilize the wires within the windings by impregnating them with varnish in a vacuum.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This prevents the wires in the winding from vibrating against each other which would abrade the wire insulation and cause premature failures.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Resin-packed motors, used in deep well submersible pumps, washing machines, and air conditioners, encapsulate the stator in plastic resin to prevent corrosion and/or reduce conducted noise.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An air gap between the stator and rotor allows it to turn.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The width of the gap has a significant effect on the motor's electrical characteristics.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It is generally made as small as possible, as a large gap weakens performance.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Conversely, gaps that are too small may create friction in addition to noise.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The armature consists of wire windings on a ferromagnetic core.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric current passing through the wire causes the magnetic field to exert a force (Lorentz force) on it, turning the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Windings are coiled wires, wrapped around a laminated, soft iron ferromagnetic core so as to form magnetic poles when energized with current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric machines come in salient- and nonsalient-pole configurations.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In a salient-pole motor the rotor and stator ferromagnetic cores have projections called poles that face each other.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Wire is wound around each pole below the pole face, which become north or south poles when current flows through the wire.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In a nonsalient-pole (distributed field or round-rotor) motor, the ferromagnetic core is a smooth cylinder, with the windings distributed evenly in slots around the circumference.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Supplying alternating current in the windings creates poles in the core that rotate continuously.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A shaded-pole motor has a winding around part of the pole that delays the phase of the magnetic field for that pole.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A commutator is a rotary electrical switch that supplies current to the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It periodically reverses the flow of current in the rotor windings as the shaft rotates.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It consists of a cylinder composed of multiple metal contact segments on the armature.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Two or more electrical contacts called *brushes* made of a soft conductive material like carbon press against the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The brushes make sliding contact with successive commutator segments as the rotator turns, supplying current to the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The windings on the rotor are connected to the commutator segments.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The commutator reverses the current direction in the rotor windings with each half turn (180°), so the torque applied to the rotor is always in the same direction.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Without this reversal, the direction of torque on each rotor winding would reverse with each half turn, stopping the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Commutated motors have been mostly replaced by brushless motors, permanent magnet motors, and induction motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The motor shaft extends outside of the motor, where it satisfies the load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Because the forces of the load are exerted beyond the outermost bearing, the load is said to be overhung.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor is supported by bearings, which allow the rotor to turn on its axis by transferring the force of axial and radial loads from the shaft to the motor housing.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Before modern electromagnetic motors, experimental motors that worked by electrostatic force were investigated.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The first electric motors were simple electrostatic devices described in experiments by Scottish monk Andrew Gordon and American experimenter Benjamin Franklin in the 1740s and 1750s.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The theoretical principle behind them, Coulomb's law, was discovered but not published, by Henry Cavendish in 1771.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This law was discovered independently by Charles-Augustin de Coulomb in 1785, who published it so that it is now known by his name.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Due to the difficulty of generating the high voltages they required, electrostatic motors were never used for practical purposes.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The invention of the electrochemical battery by Alessandro Volta in 1799 made the production of persistent electric currents possible.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Hans Christian Ørsted discovered in 1820 that an electric current creates a magnetic field, which can exert a force on a magnet.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It only took a few weeks for André-Marie Ampère to develop the first formulation of the electromagnetic interaction and present the Ampère's force law, that described the production of mechanical force by the interaction of an electric current and a magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Michael Faraday gave the first demonstration of the effect with a rotary motion on 3 September 1821 in the basement of the Royal Institution.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A free-hanging wire was dipped into a pool of mercury, on which a permanent magnet (PM) was placed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] When a current was passed through the wire, the wire rotated around the magnet, showing that the current gave rise to a close circular magnetic field around the wire.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Faraday published the results of his discovery in the *Quarterly Journal of Science*, and sent copies of his paper along with pocket-sized models of his device to colleagues around the world so they could also witness the phenomenon of electromagnetic rotations.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This motor is often demonstrated in physics experiments, substituting brine for (toxic) mercury.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Barlow's wheel was an early refinement to this Faraday demonstration, although these and similar homopolar motors remained unsuited to practical application until late in the century.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 1827, Hungarian physicist Ányos Jedlik started experimenting with electromagnetic coils.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] After Jedlik solved the technical problems of continuous rotation with the invention of the commutator, he called his early devices "electromagnetic self-rotors".
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Although they were used only for teaching, in 1828 Jedlik demonstrated the first device to contain the three main components of practical DC motors: the stator, rotor and commutator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The device employed no permanent magnets, as the magnetic fields of both the stationary and revolving components were produced solely by the currents flowing through their windings.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The first commutator DC electric motor capable of turning machinery was invented by English scientist William Sturgeon in 1832.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Following Sturgeon's work, a commutator-type direct-current electric motor was built by American inventors Thomas Davenport and Emily Davenport, which he patented in 1837.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The motors ran at up to 600 revolutions per minute, and powered machine tools and a printing press.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Due to the high cost of primary battery power, the motors were commercially unsuccessful and bankrupted the Davenports.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Several inventors followed Sturgeon in the development of DC motors, but all encountered the same battery cost issues.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] As no electricity distribution system was available at the time, no practical commercial market emerged for these motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] After many other more or less successful attempts with relatively weak rotating and reciprocating apparatus German-Russian Moritz von Jacobi created the first real useful rotating electric motor in May 1834.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It developed remarkable mechanical output power.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] His motor set a world record, which Jacobi improved four years later in September 1838.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] His second motor was powerful enough to drive an electric boat with 14 people across a wide river.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It was also in 1839–1840 that other developers managed to build motors with similar and then higher performance.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 1827–1828, Jedlik built a device using similar principles to those used in his electromagnetic self-rotors that was capable of useful work.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] He built a model electric vehicle that same year.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A major turning point came in 1864, when Antonio Pacinotti first described the ring armature (although initially conceived in a DC generator, i.e. a dynamo).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This featured symmetrically grouped coils closed upon themselves and connected to the bars of a commutator, the brushes of which delivered practically non-fluctuating current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The first commercially successful DC motors followed the developments by Zénobe Gramme who, in 1871, reinvented Pacinotti's design and adopted some solutions by Werner Siemens.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A benefit to DC machines came from the discovery of the reversibility of the electric machine, which was announced by Siemens in 1867 and observed by Pacinotti in 1869.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Gramme accidentally demonstrated it on the occasion of the 1873 Vienna World's Fair, when he connected two such DC devices up to 2 km from each other, using one of them as a generator and the other as motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The drum rotor was introduced by Friedrich von Hefner-Alteneck of Siemens & Halske to replace Pacinotti's ring armature in 1872, thus improving the machine efficiency.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The laminated rotor was introduced by Siemens & Halske the following year, achieving reduced iron losses and increased induced voltages.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 1880, Jonas Wenström provided the rotor with slots for housing the winding, further increasing the efficiency.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 1886, Frank Julian Sprague invented the first practical DC motor, a non-sparking device that maintained relatively constant speed under variable loads.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This allowed Sprague to use electric motors to invent the first electric trolley system in 1887–88 in Richmond, Virginia, the electric elevator and control system in 1892, and the electric subway with independently powered centrally controlled cars.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The latter were first installed in 1892 in Chicago by the South Side Elevated Railroad, where it became popularly known as the "L".
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Sprague's motor and related inventions led to an explosion of interest and use in electric motors for industry.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The development of electric motors of acceptable efficiency was delayed for several decades by failure to recognize the extreme importance of an air gap between the rotor and stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Efficient designs have a comparatively small air gap.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Louis motor, long used in classrooms to illustrate motor principles, is inefficient for the same reason, as well as appearing nothing like a modern motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors revolutionized industry.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Industrial processes were no longer limited by power transmission using line shafts, belts, compressed air or hydraulic pressure.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Instead, every machine could be equipped with its own power source, providing easy control at the point of use, and improving power transmission efficiency.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors applied in agriculture eliminated human and animal muscle power from tasks such as handling grain and pumping water.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Household uses (such as washing machines, dishwashers, fans, air conditioners and refrigerators) of electric motors reduced heavy labor in the home and made higher standards of convenience, comfort and safety possible.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Today, electric motors consume more than half of the electric energy produced in the US.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 1824, French physicist François Arago formulated the existence of rotating magnetic fields, termed Arago's rotations, which, by manually turning switches on and off, Walter Baily demonstrated in 1879 as in effect the first primitive induction motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In the 1880s many inventors were trying to develop workable AC motors because AC's advantages in long-distance high-voltage transmission were offset by the inability to operate motors on AC.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The first alternating-current commutatorless induction motor was invented by Galileo Ferraris in 1885.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Ferraris was able to improve his first design by producing more advanced setups in 1886.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Possible industrial development was envisioned by Nikola Tesla, who invented independently his induction motor in 1887 and obtained a patent in May 1888.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] One of the patents Tesla filed in 1887, however, also described a shorted-winding-rotor induction motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] George Westinghouse, who had already acquired rights from Ferraris (US$1,000), promptly bought Tesla's patents (US$60,000 plus US$2.50 per sold hp, paid until 1897), employed Tesla to develop his motors, and assigned C.F.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Scott to help Tesla; however, Tesla left for other pursuits in 1889.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The constant speed AC induction motor was found not to be suitable for street cars, but Westinghouse engineers successfully adapted it to power a mining operation in Telluride, Colorado in 1891.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Westinghouse achieved its first practical induction motor in 1892 and developed a line of polyphase 60 hertz induction motors in 1893, but these early Westinghouse motors were two-phase motors with wound rotors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Lamme later developed a rotating bar winding rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Steadfast in his promotion of three-phase development, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky invented the three-phase induction motor in 1889, of both types cage-rotor and wound rotor with a starting rheostat, and the three-limb transformer in 1890.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] After an agreement between AEG and Maschinenfabrik Oerlikon, Doliwo-Dobrowolski and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown developed larger models, namely a 20-hp squirrel cage and a 100-hp wound rotor with a starting rheostat.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] These were the first three-phase asynchronous motors suitable for practical operation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Since 1889, similar developments of three-phase machinery were started Wenström.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] At the 1891 Frankfurt International Electrotechnical Exhibition, the first long distance three-phase system was successfully presented.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It was rated 15 kV and extended over 175 km from the Lauffen waterfall on the Neckar river.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The Lauffen power station included a 240 kW 86 V 40 Hz alternator and a step-up transformer while at the exhibition a step-down transformer fed a 100-hp three-phase induction motor that powered an artificial waterfall, representing the transfer of the original power source.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The three-phase induction is now used for the vast majority of commercial applications.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky claimed that Tesla's motor was not practical because of two-phase pulsations, which prompted him to persist in his three-phase work.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The General Electric Company began developing three-phase induction motors in 1891.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] By 1896, General Electric and Westinghouse signed a cross-licensing agreement for the bar-winding-rotor design, later called the squirrel-cage rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Induction motor improvements flowing from these inventions and innovations were such that a 100-horsepower induction motor currently has the same mounting dimensions as a 7.5-horsepower motor in 1897.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In 2022, electric motor sales were estimated to be 800 million units, increasing by 10% annually.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors consume ≈50% of the world's electricity.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Since the 1980s, the market share of DC motors has declined in favor of AC motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A DC motor is usually supplied through a split ring commutator as described above.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] AC motors' commutation can be achieved using either a slip ring commutator or external commutation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It can be fixed-speed or variable-speed control type, and can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Universal motors can run on either AC or DC.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] DC motors can be operated at variable speeds by adjusting the voltage applied to the terminals or by using pulse-width modulation (PWM).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] AC motors operated at a fixed speed are generally powered directly from the grid or through motor soft starters.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] AC motors operated at variable speeds are powered with various power inverter, variable-frequency drive or electronic commutator technologies.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The term electronic commutator is usually associated with self-commutated brushless DC motor and switched reluctance motor applications.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Electric motors operate on one of three physical principles: magnetism, electrostatics and piezoelectricity.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In magnetic motors, magnetic fields are formed in both the rotor and the stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The product between these two fields gives rise to a force and thus a torque on the motor shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] One or both of these fields changes as the rotor turns.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This is done by switching the poles on and off at the right time, or varying the strength of the pole.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Motors can be designed to operate on DC current, on AC current, or some types can work on either.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] AC motors can be either asynchronous or synchronous.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Synchronous motors require the rotor to turn at the same speed as the stator's rotating field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Asynchronous rotors relax this constraint.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A fractional-horsepower motor either has a rating below about 1 horsepower (0.746 kW), or is manufactured with a frame size smaller than a standard 1 HP motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Many household and industrial motors are in the fractional-horsepower class.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Rotation is equal to synchronous speed (motor-stator-field speed).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In SCIM, fixed-speed operation rotation is equal to synchronous speed, less slip speed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In non-slip energy-recovery systems, WRIM is usually used for motor-starting but can be used to vary load speed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Whereas induction- and synchronous-motor drives are typically with either six-step or sinusoidal-waveform output, BLDC-motor drives are usually with trapezoidal-current waveform; the behavior of both sinusoidal and trapezoidal PM machines is, however, identical in terms of their fundamental aspects.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In variable-speed operation, WRIM is used in slip-energy recovery and double-fed induction-machine applications.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A cage winding is a short-circuited squirrel-cage rotor, a wound winding is connected externally through slip rings.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Mostly single-phase with some three-phase.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Most DC motors are small permanent magnet (PM) types.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They contain a brushed internal mechanical commutation to reverse motor windings' current in synchronism with rotation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A commutated DC motor has a set of rotating windings wound on an armature mounted on a rotating shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Thus, every brushed DC motor has AC flowing through its windings.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Current flows through one or more pairs of brushes that touch the commutator; the brushes connect an external source of electric power to the rotating armature.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotating armature consists of one or more wire coils wound around a laminated, magnetically "soft" ferromagnetic core.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Current from the brushes flows through the commutator and one winding of the armature, making it a temporary magnet (an electromagnet).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The magnetic field produced interacts with a stationary magnetic field produced by either PMs or another winding (a field coil), as part of the motor frame.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The force between the two magnetic fields rotates the shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The commutator switches power to the coils as the rotor turns, keeping the poles from ever fully aligning with the magnetic poles of the stator field, so that the rotor keeps turning as long as power is applied.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Many of the limitations of the classic commutator DC motor are due to the need for brushes to maintain contact with the commutator, creating friction.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The brushes create sparks while crossing the insulating gaps between commutator sections.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Depending on the commutator design, the brushes may create short circuits between adjacent sections—and hence coil ends.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Furthermore, the rotor coils' inductance causes the voltage across each to rise when its circuit opens, increasing the sparking.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This sparking limits the maximum speed of the machine, as too-rapid sparking will overheat, erode, or even melt the commutator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The current density per unit area of the brushes, in combination with their resistivity, limits the motor's output.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Crossing the gaps also generates electrical noise; sparking generates RFI.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Brushes eventually wear out and require replacement, and the commutator itself is subject to wear and maintenance or replacement.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The commutator assembly on a large motor is a costly element, requiring precision assembly of many parts.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] On small motors, the commutator is usually permanently integrated into the rotor, so replacing it usually requires replacing the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] While most commutators are cylindrical, some are flat, segmented discs mounted on an insulator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Large brushes create a large contact area, which maximizes motor output, while small brushes have low mass to maximize the speed at which the motor can run without excessive sparking.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] (Small brushes are desirable for their lower cost.) Stiffer brush springs can be used to make brushes of a given mass work at a higher speed, despite greater friction losses (lower efficiency) and accelerated brush and commutator wear.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Therefore, DC motor brush design entails a trade-off between output power, speed, and efficiency/wear.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A permanent magnet (PM) motor does not have a field winding on the stator frame, relying instead on PMs to provide the magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Compensating windings in series with the armature may be used on large motors to improve commutation under load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This field is fixed and cannot be adjusted for speed control.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Historically, PMs could not be made to retain high flux if they were disassembled; field windings were more practical to obtain the needed flux.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] To minimize overall weight and size, miniature PM motors may use high energy magnets made with neodymium; most are neodymium-iron-boron alloy.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] With their higher flux density, electric machines with high-energy PMs are at least competitive with all optimally designed singly-fed synchronous and induction electric machines.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Some of the problems of the brushed DC motor are eliminated in the BLDC design.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In this motor, the mechanical "rotating switch" or commutator is replaced by an external electronic switch synchronised to the rotor's position.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] BLDC motors are typically 85%+ efficient, reaching up to 96.5%, while brushed DC motors are typically 75–80% efficient.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The BLDC motor's characteristic trapezoidal counter-electromotive force (CEMF) waveform is derived partly from the stator windings being evenly distributed, and partly from the placement of the rotor's permanent magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Also known as electronically commutated DC or inside-out DC motors, the stator windings of trapezoidal BLDC motors can be single-phase, two-phase or three-phase and use Hall effect sensors mounted on their windings for rotor position sensing and low cost closed-loop commutator control.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] BLDC motors are commonly used where precise speed control is necessary, as in computer disk drives or video cassette recorders.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The spindles within CD, CD-ROM (etc.) drives, and mechanisms within office products, such as fans, laser printers and photocopiers.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Modern BLDC motors range in power from a fraction of a watt to many kilowatts.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Larger BLDC motors rated up to about 100 kW are used in electric vehicles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They also find use in electric model aircraft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The switched reluctance motor (SRM) has no brushes or permanent magnets, and the rotor has no electric currents.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Torque comes from a slight misalignment of poles on the rotor with poles on the stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor aligns itself with the magnetic field of the stator, while the stator field windings are sequentially energized to rotate the stator field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The magnetic flux created by the field windings follows the path of least magnetic sending the flux through rotor poles that are closest to the energized poles of the stator, thereby magnetizing those poles of the rotor and creating torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] As the rotor turns, different windings are energized, keeping the rotor turning.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] SRMs are used in some appliances and vehicles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A commutated, electrically excited, series or parallel wound motor is referred to as a universal motor because it can be designed to operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A universal motor can operate well on AC because the current in both the field and the armature coils (and hence the resultant magnetic fields) synchronously reverse polarity, and hence the resulting mechanical force occurs in a constant direction of rotation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Operating at normal power line frequencies, universal motors are often used in sub-kilowatt applications.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Universal motors formed the basis of the traditional railway traction motor in electric railways.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In this application, using AC power on a motor designed to run on DC would experience efficiency losses due to eddy current heating of their magnetic components, particularly the motor field pole-pieces that, for DC, would have used solid (un-laminated) iron.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An advantage is that AC power may be used on motors that specifically have high starting torque and compact design if high running speeds are used.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] By contrast, maintenance is higher and lifetimes are shortened.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Such motors are used in devices that are not heavily used, and have high starting-torque demands.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Multiple taps on the field coil provide (imprecise) stepped speed control.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Household blenders that advertise many speeds typically combine a field coil with several taps and a diode that can be inserted in series with the motor (causing the motor to run on half-wave rectified AC).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Universal motors also lend themselves to electronic speed control and, as such, are a choice for devices such as domestic washing machines.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The motor can agitate the drum (both forwards and in reverse) by switching the field winding with respect to the armature.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Whereas SCIMs cannot turn a shaft faster than allowed by the power line frequency, universal motors can run at much higher speeds.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This makes them useful for appliances such as blenders, vacuum cleaners, and hair dryers where high speed and light weight are desirable.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They are also commonly used in portable power tools, such as drills, sanders, circular and jig saws, where the motor's characteristics work well.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Many vacuum cleaner and weed trimmer motors exceed 10,000 rpm, while miniature grinders may exceed 30,000 rpm.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] AC induction and synchronous motors are optimized for operation on single-phase or polyphase sinusoidal or quasi-sinusoidal waveform power such as supplied for fixed-speed applications by the AC power grid or for variable-speed application from variable-frequency drive (VFD) controllers.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An induction motor is an asynchronous AC motor where power is transferred to the rotor by electromagnetic induction, much like transformer action.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An induction motor resembles a rotating transformer, because the stator (stationary part) is essentially the primary side of the transformer and the rotor (rotating part) is the secondary side.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Polyphase induction motors are widely used in industry.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Induction motors may be divided into Squirrel Cage Induction Motors (SCIM) and Wound Rotor Induction Motors (WRIM).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] SCIMs have a heavy winding made up of solid bars, usually aluminum or copper, electrically connected by rings at the ends of the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The bars and rings as a whole are much like an animal's rotating exercise cage.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Currents induced into this winding provide the rotor magnetic field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The shape of the rotor bars determines the speed-torque characteristics.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] At low speeds, the current induced in the squirrel cage is nearly at line frequency and tends to stay in the outer parts of the cage.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] As the motor accelerates, the slip frequency becomes lower, and more current reaches the interior.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] By shaping the bars to change the resistance of the winding portions in the interior and outer parts of the cage, a variable resistance is effectively inserted in the rotor circuit.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] However, most such motors employ uniform bars.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In a WRIM, the rotor winding is made of many turns of insulated wire and is connected to slip rings on the motor shaft.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] An external resistor or other control device can be connected in the rotor circuit.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Resistors allow control of the motor speed, although dissipating significant power.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A converter can be fed from the rotor circuit and return the slip-frequency power that would otherwise be wasted into the power system through an inverter or separate motor-generator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] WRIMs are used primarily to start a high inertia load or a load that requires high starting torque across the full speed range.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] By correctly selecting the resistors used in the secondary resistance or slip ring starter, the motor is able to produce maximum torque at a relatively low supply current from zero speed to full speed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Motor speed can be changed because the motor's torque curve is effectively modified by the amount of resistance connected to the rotor circuit.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Increasing resistance lowers the speed of maximum torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] If the resistance is increased beyond the point where the maximum torque occurs at zero speed, the torque is further reduced.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] When used with a load that has a torque curve that increases with speed, the motor operates at the speed where the torque developed by the motor is equal to the load torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Reducing the load causes the motor to speed up, while increasing the load causes the motor to slow down until the load and motor torque are again equal.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Operated in this manner, the slip losses are dissipated in the secondary resistors and can be significant.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The speed regulation and net efficiency is poor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A torque motor can operate indefinitely while stalled, that is, with the rotor blocked from turning, without incurring damage.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In this mode of operation, the motor applies a steady torque to the load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A common application is the supply- and take-up reel motors in a tape drive.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In this application, driven by a low voltage, the characteristics of these motors apply a steady light tension to the tape whether or not the capstan is feeding tape past the tape heads.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Driven from a higher voltage (delivering a higher torque), torque motors can achieve fast-forward and rewind operation without requiring additional mechanics such as gears or clutches.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] In the computer gaming world, torque motors are used in force feedback steering wheels.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Another common application is to control the throttle of an internal combustion engine with an electronic governor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The motor works against a return spring to move the throttle in accord with the governor output.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The latter monitors engine speed by counting electrical pulses from the ignition system or from a magnetic pickup and depending on the speed, makes small adjustments to the amount of current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] If the engine slows down relative to the desired speed, the current increases, producing more torque, pulling against the return spring and opening the throttle.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Should the engine run too fast, the governor reduces the current, allowing the return spring to pull back and reduce the throttle.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A synchronous electric motor is an AC motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It includes a rotor spinning with coils passing magnets at the same frequency as the AC and produces a magnetic field to drive it.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] It has zero slip under typical operating conditions.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] By contrast induction motors must slip to produce torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] One type of synchronous motor is like an induction motor except that the rotor is excited by a DC field.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Slip rings and brushes conduct current to the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor poles connect to each other and move at the same speed.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Another type, for low load torque, has flats ground onto a conventional squirrel-cage rotor to create discrete poles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Yet another, as made by Hammond for its pre-World War II clocks, and in older Hammond organs, has no rotor windings and discrete poles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The clock requires manual starting by a small knob on the back, while the older Hammond organs had an auxiliary starting motor connected by a spring-loaded manually operated switch.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Hysteresis synchronous motors typically are (essentially) two-phase motors with a phase-shifting capacitor for one phase.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] They start like induction motors, but when slip rate decreases sufficiently, the rotor (a smooth cylinder) becomes temporarily magnetized.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Its distributed poles make it act like a permanent magnet synchronous motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] The rotor material, like that of a common nail, stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized with little difficulty.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Once running, the rotor poles stay in place; they do not drift.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Low-power synchronous timing motors (such as those for traditional electric clocks) may have multi-pole permanent magnet external cup rotors, and use shading coils to provide starting torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] *Telechron* clock motors have shaded poles for starting torque, and a two-spoke ring rotor that performs like a discrete two-pole rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Doubly fed electric motors have two independent multiphase winding sets, which contribute active (i.e., working) power to the energy conversion process, with at least one of the winding sets electronically controlled for variable speed operation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Two independent multiphase winding sets (i.e., dual armature) are the maximum provided in a single package without topology duplication.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Doubly fed electric motors have an effective constant torque speed range that is twice synchronous speed for a given frequency of excitation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] This is twice the constant torque speed range as singly-fed electric machines, which have only one active winding set.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] A doubly fed motor allows for a smaller electronic converter but the cost of the rotor winding and slip rings may offset the saving in the power electronics components.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p01] Difficulties affect controlling speed near synchronous speed limit applications.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The coreless or ironless DC motor is a specialized permanent magnet DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Optimized for rapid acceleration, the rotor is constructed without an iron core.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The rotor can take the form of a winding-filled cylinder, or a self-supporting structure comprising only wire and bonding material.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The rotor can fit inside the stator magnets; a magnetically soft stationary cylinder inside the rotor provides a return path for the stator magnetic flux.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A second arrangement has the rotor winding basket surrounding the stator magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] In that design, the rotor fits inside a magnetically soft cylinder that can serve as the motor housing, and provides a return path for the flux.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Because the rotor is much lower in mass compared to a conventional rotor, it can accelerate much more rapidly, often achieving a mechanical time constant under one millisecond.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This is especially true if the windings use aluminum rather than (heavier) copper.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The rotor has no metal mass to act as a heat sink; even small motors must be cooled.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Overheating can be an issue for these designs.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The vibrating alert of cellular phones can be generated by cylindrical permanent-magnet motors, or disc-shaped types that have a thin multipolar disc field magnet, and an intentionally unbalanced molded-plastic rotor structure with two bonded coreless coils.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Metal brushes and a flat commutator switch power to the rotor coils.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Related limited-travel actuators have no core and a bonded coil placed between the poles of high-flux thin permanent magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] These are the fast head positioners for rigid-disk ("hard disk") drives.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Although the contemporary design differs considerably from that of loudspeakers, it is still loosely (and incorrectly) referred to as a "voice coil" structure, because some earlier rigid-disk-drive heads moved in straight lines, and had a drive structure much like that of a loudspeaker.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The printed armature or pancake motor has windings shaped as a disc running between arrays of high-flux magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The magnets are arranged in a circle facing the rotor spaced to form an axial air gap.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This design is commonly known as the pancake motor because of its flat profile.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The armature (originally formed on a printed circuit board) is made from punched copper sheets that are laminated together using advanced composites to form a thin, rigid disc.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The armature does not have a separate ring commutator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The brushes move directly on the armature surface making the whole design compact.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] An alternative design is to use wound copper wire laid flat with a central conventional commutator, in a flower and petal shape.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The windings are typically stabilized with electrical epoxy potting systems.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] These are filled epoxies that have moderate, mixed viscosity and a long gel time.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] They are highlighted by low shrinkage and low exotherm, and are typically UL 1446 recognized as a potting compound insulated with 180 °C (356 °F), Class H rating.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The unique advantage of ironless DC motors is the absence of cogging (torque variations caused by changing attraction between the iron and the magnets).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Parasitic eddy currents cannot form in the rotor as it is totally ironless, although iron rotors are laminated.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This can greatly improve efficiency, but variable-speed controllers must use a higher switching rate (>40 kHz) or DC because of decreased electromagnetic induction.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] These motors were invented to drive the capstan(s) of magnetic tape drives, where minimal time to reach operating speed and minimal stopping distance were critical.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Pancake motors are widely used in high-performance servo-controlled systems, robotic systems, industrial automation and medical devices.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Due to the variety of constructions now available, the technology is used in applications from high temperature military to low cost pump and basic servos.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Another approach (Magnax) is to use a single stator sandwiched between two rotors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] One such design has produced peak power of 15 kW/kg, sustained power around 7.5 kW/kg.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This yokeless axial flux motor offers a shorter flux path, keeping the magnets further from the axis.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The design allows zero winding overhang; 100 percent of the windings are active.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This is enhanced with the use of rectangular-crosssection copper wire.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The motors can be stacked to work in parallel.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Instabilities are minimized by ensuring that the two rotor discs put equal and opposing forces onto the stator disc.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The rotors are connected directly to one another via a shaft ring, cancelling out the magnetic forces.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A transverse flux motor (TFM) is a type of motor characterized by a magnetic flux path that is transverse to the axis of rotation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The flux path is not completely axial or radial, but instead travels through U-shaped magnetic cores that comprise the stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Transverse flux motors have a single winding for each phase that is wrapped circumferentially around the stator.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This winding configuration allows for the number of machine poles to be decoupled from the size of the windings, leading to a high torque density and number of poles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Transverse flux motors suffer from cogging and ripple torque, and are complicated and expensive to design and produce.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] These factors have contributed to their niche role in the landscape of electric motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A servomotor is a motor that is used within a position-control or speed-control feedback system.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Servomotors are used in applications such as machine tools, pen plotters, and other process systems.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Motors intended for use in a servomechanism must have predictable characteristics for speed, torque, and power.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The speed/torque curve is important and is high ratio for a servomotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Dynamic response characteristics such as winding inductance and rotor inertia are important; these factors limit performance.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Large, powerful, but slow-responding servo loops may use conventional AC or DC motors and drive systems with position or speed feedback.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] As dynamic response requirements increase, more specialized motor designs such as coreless motors are used.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] AC motors' superior power density and acceleration characteristics tends to favor permanent magnet synchronous, BLDC, induction, and SRM drive approaches.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A servo system differs from some stepper motor applications in that position feedback is continuous while the motor is running.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A stepper system inherently operates open-loop—relying on the motor not to "miss steps" for short term accuracy—with any feedback such as a "home" switch or position encoder external to the motor system.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Stepper motors are typically used to provide precise rotations.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] An internal rotor containing permanent magnets or a magnetically soft rotor with salient poles is controlled by a set of electronically switched external magnets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A stepper motor may also be thought of as a cross between a DC electric motor and a rotary solenoid.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] As each coil is energized in turn, the rotor aligns itself with the magnetic field produced by the energized field winding.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Unlike a synchronous motor, the stepper motor may not rotate continuously; instead, it moves in steps—starting and then stopping—advancing from one position to the next as field windings are energized and de-energized in sequence.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Depending on the sequence, the rotor may turn forwards or backwards, and it may change direction, stop, speed up or slow down at any time.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Simple stepper motor drivers entirely energize or entirely de-energize the field windings, leading the rotor to "cog" to a limited number of positions.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Microstepping drivers can proportionally control the power to the field windings, allowing the rotors to position between cog points and rotate smoothly.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Computer-controlled stepper motors are one of the most versatile positioning systems, particularly as part of a digital servo-controlled system.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Stepper motors can be rotated to a specific angle in discrete steps with ease, and hence stepper motors are used for read/write head positioning in early disk drives, where the precision and speed they offered could correctly position the read/write head.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] As drive density increased, precision and speed limitations made them obsolete for hard drives—the precision limitation made them unusable, and the speed limitation made them uncompetitive—thus newer hard disk drives use voice coil-based head actuator systems.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Stepper motors are often used in computer printers, optical scanners, and digital photocopiers to move the active element, the print head carriage (inkjet printers), and the platen or feed rollers.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] So-called quartz analog wristwatches contain the smallest commonplace stepping motors; they have one coil, draw little power, and have a permanent magnet rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The same kind of motor drives battery-powered quartz clocks.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Some of these watches, such as chronographs, contain more than one stepper motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Closely related in design to three-phase AC synchronous motors, stepper motors and SRMs are classified as variable reluctance motor type.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A linear motor is essentially any electric motor that has been "unrolled" so that, instead of producing torque (rotation), it produces a straight-line force along its length.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Linear motors are most commonly induction motors or stepper motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Linear motors are commonly found in roller-coasters where the rapid motion of the motorless railcar is controlled by the rail.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] They are also used in maglev trains, where the train "flies" over the ground.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] On a smaller scale, the 1978 era HP 7225A pen plotter used two linear stepper motors to move the pen along the X and Y axes.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] An electrostatic motor is based on the attraction and repulsion of electric charge.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Usually, electrostatic motors are the dual of conventional coil-based motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] They typically require a high-voltage power supply, although small motors employ lower voltages.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Conventional electric motors instead employ magnetic attraction and repulsion, and require high current at low voltages.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] In the 1750s, the first electrostatic motors were developed by Benjamin Franklin and Andrew Gordon.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electrostatic motors find frequent use in micro-electro-mechanical systems (MEMS) where their drive voltages are below 100 volts, and where moving, charged plates are far easier to fabricate than coils and iron cores.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The molecular machinery that runs living cells is often based on linear and rotary electrostatic motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A piezoelectric motor or piezo motor is a type of electric motor based upon the change in shape of a piezoelectric material when an electric field is applied.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Piezoelectric motors make use of the converse piezoelectric effect whereby the material produces acoustic or ultrasonic vibrations to produce linear or rotary motion.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] In one mechanism, the elongation in a single plane is used to make a series of stretches and position holds, similar to the way a caterpillar moves.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] An electrically powered spacecraft propulsion system uses electric motor technology to propel spacecraft in outer space.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Most systems are based on electrically accelerating propellant to high speed, while some systems are based on electrodynamic tethers principles of propulsion to the magnetosphere.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] An electric motor converts electrical energy to mechanical energy through the force between two opposed magnetic fields.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] At least one of the two magnetic fields must be created by an electromagnet through the magnetic field caused by an electrical current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The most general approaches to calculating the forces in motors use tensor notation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] ; i.e., difference between synchronous speed and slip speed, which provides the relative movement needed for current induction in the rotor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The movement of armature windings of a direct-current or universal motor through a magnetic field, induce a voltage in them.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This voltage tends to oppose the motor supply voltage and so is called "back electromotive force (EMF)".
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The voltage is proportional to the running speed of the motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The back EMF of the motor, plus the voltage drop across the winding internal resistance and brushes, must equal the voltage at the brushes.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This provides the fundamental mechanism of speed regulation in a DC motor.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] If the mechanical load increases, the motor slows down; a lower back EMF results, and more current is drawn from the supply.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] This increased current provides the additional torque to balance the load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] In AC machines, it is sometimes useful to consider a back EMF source within the machine; this is of particular concern for close speed regulation of induction motors on VFDs.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Motor losses are mainly due to resistive losses in windings, core losses and mechanical losses in bearings, and aerodynamic losses, particularly where cooling fans are present, also occur.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Losses also occur in commutation, mechanical commutators spark; electronic commutators and also dissipate heat.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] where V is input voltage, I is input current, T is output torque, and $\omega$ is output angular velocity.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] It is possible to derive analytically the point of maximum efficiency.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] It is typically at less than 1/2 the stall torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Various national regulatory authorities have enacted legislation to encourage the manufacture and use of higher-efficiency motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electric motors have efficiencies ranging from around 15%-20% for shaded pole motors, up to 98% for permanent magnet motors, with efficiency also dependent on load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Peak efficiency is usually at 75% of the rated load.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] So (as an example) a 10 HP motor is most efficient when driving a load that requires 7.5 HP.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Efficiency also depends on motor size; larger motors tend to be more efficient.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] From this, he showed that the most efficient motors are likely to have relatively large magnetic poles.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] However, the equation only directly relates to non PM motors.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electromagnetic motors derive torque from the vector product of the interacting fields.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Calculating torque requires knowledge of the fields in the air gap.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Once these have been established, the torque is the integral of all the force vectors multiplied by the vector's radius.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The current flowing in the winding produces the fields.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] For a motor using a magnetic material the field is not proportional to the current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] A figure relating the current to the torque can inform motor selection.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The maximum torque for a motor depends on the maximum current, absent thermal considerations.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Some applications require bursts of torque beyond the maximum, such as bursts to accelerate an electric vehicle from standstill.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Always limited by magnetic core saturation or safe operating temperature rise and voltage, the capacity for torque bursts beyond the maximum differs significantly across motor/generator types.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electric machines without a transformer circuit topology, such as that of WRSMs or PMSMs, cannot provide torque bursts without saturating the magnetic core.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] At that point, additional current cannot increase torque.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Furthermore, the permanent magnet assembly of PMSMs can be irreparably damaged.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electric machines that rely on induction or asynchronous principles short-circuit one port of the transformer circuit and as a result, the reactive impedance of the transformer circuit becomes dominant as slip increases, which limits the magnitude of active (i.e., real) current.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Torque bursts two to three times higher than the maximum design torque are realizable.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The brushless wound-rotor synchronous doubly fed (BWRSDF) machine is the only electric machine with a truly dual ported transformer circuit topology (i.e., both ports independently excited with no short-circuited port).
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The dual ported transformer circuit topology is known to be unstable and requires a multiphase slip-ring-brush assembly to propagate limited power to the rotor winding set.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Torque bursts greater than eight times operating torque have been calculated.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The continuous torque density of conventional electric machines is determined by the size of the air-gap area and the back-iron depth, which are determined by the power rating of the armature winding set, the speed of the machine, and the achievable air-gap flux density before core saturation.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Despite the high coercivity of neodymium or samarium-cobalt permanent magnets, continuous torque density is virtually the same amongst electric machines with optimally designed armature winding sets.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Continuous torque density relates to method of cooling and permissible operation period before destruction by overheating of windings or permanent magnet damage.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Other sources state that various e-machine topologies have differing torque density.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] where—specific torque density is normalized to 1.0 for the surface permanent magnet (SPM)—brushless ac, 180° current conduction.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Torque density is approximately four times greater for liquid cooled motors, compared to those which are air cooled.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Another source notes that PMSM up to 1 MW have considerably higher torque density than induction machines.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The continuous power density is determined by the product of the continuous torque density and the constant torque speed range.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] Electric motors can achieve densities of up to 20 kW/kg, meaning 20 kilowatts of output power per kilogram.
[src:dc-motors/electric-motor-p02] The latter source, which can be responsible for the "whining noise" of electric motors, is called electromagnetically induced acoustic noise.
